# Drop missing values
data = data.dropna()

# Convert categorical features to numerical
categorical_features = data.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns.tolist()

# Display unique values for categorical features
for feature in categorical_features:
    print(f"{feature}:")
    print('\t' + str(data[feature].unique()))

# Replace values for consistency
category_mapping = {
    'PreferredLoginDevice': {'Mobile Phone': 'Phone'},
    'PreferredPaymentMode': {'COD': 'Cash on Delivery', 'CC': 'Credit Card'},
    'PreferedOrderCat': {'Mobile': 'Mobile Phone'}
}

for col, mapping in category_mapping.items():
    data[col] = data[col].replace(mapping)

# Encode categorical features
for feature in categorical_features:
    label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
    data[feature] = label_encoder.fit_transform(data[feature])

# Verify the changes
for feature in categorical_features:
    print(f"{feature}:")
    print('\t' + str(data[feature].unique()))

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest, f_classif, chi2, RFE
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

def autoFeatureSelector(data, methods=['pearson', 'chi-square', 'rfe', 'log-reg', 'rf', 'anova'], num_feats=10):
    # Check if methods list is empty
    if not methods:
        raise ValueError("At least one feature selection method must be provided.")
    
    # Extract features and target variable
    numeric_columns = data.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns.tolist()
    X = data[numeric_columns].drop('Churn', axis=1)
    y = data['Churn']
    
    # Clip values
    max_val = 5000
    X = np.clip(X, a_min=None, a_max=max_val)
    
    selected_features = []
    
    for method in methods:
        if method == 'pearson':
            # Calculate Pearson correlation coefficients
            pearson_corr = X.corrwith(y)
            cor_support = pearson_corr.abs().nlargest(num_feats).index
            selected_features.append(('Pearson', cor_support))
        
        elif method == 'chi-square':
            # Apply chi-square test to select features
            chi_selector = SelectKBest(score_func=chi2, k=num_feats)
            chi_selector.fit(X, y)
            chi_support = chi_selector.get_support(indices=True)
            selected_features.append(('Chi-2', X.columns[chi_support]))
        
        elif method == 'rfe':
            # Initialize the model
            model = LogisticRegression()
            # Apply Recursive Feature Elimination
            rfe_selector = RFE(estimator=model, n_features_to_select=num_feats, step=1)
            rfe_selector.fit(X, y)
            rfe_support = rfe_selector.get_support(indices=True)
            selected_features.append(('RFE', X.columns[rfe_support]))
        
        elif method == 'log-reg':
            # Initialize the model
            model = LogisticRegression()
            # Apply SelectFromModel with Logistic Regression as estimator
            embed_lr_selector = SelectFromModel(estimator=model, max_features=num_feats)
            embed_lr_selector.fit(X, y)
            embed_lr_support = embed_lr_selector.get_support(indices=True)
            selected_features.append(('Logistics', X.columns[embed_lr_support]))
        
        elif method == 'rf':
            # Initialize the model
            model = RandomForestClassifier()
            # Apply SelectFromModel with Random Forest as estimator
            embed_rf_selector = SelectFromModel(estimator=model, max_features=num_feats)
            embed_rf_selector.fit(X, y)
            embed_rf_support = embed_rf_selector.get_support(indices=True)
            selected_features.append(('Random Forest', X.columns[embed_rf_support]))
        
        elif method == 'anova':
            # Apply ANOVA test to select features
            anova_selector = SelectKBest(score_func=f_classif, k=num_feats)
            anova_selector.fit(X, y)
            anova_support = anova_selector.get_support(indices=True)
            selected_features.append(('ANOVA', X.columns[anova_support]))

    # Create DataFrame to store feature selection results
    feature_selection_df = pd.DataFrame({'Feature': X.columns})
    
    for method, support in selected_features:
        feature_selection_df[method] = feature_selection_df['Feature'].apply(lambda x: x in support)

    # Calculate total selected times for each feature
    feature_selection_df['Total'] = feature_selection_df.iloc[:, 1:].sum(axis=1)

    # Sort DataFrame based on total selected times
    feature_selection_df = feature_selection_df.sort_values(['Total', 'Feature'], ascending=False)

    # Get top num_feats features
    best_features = feature_selection_df.head(num_feats)

    return best_features

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, roc_auc_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix
# Random Forest Model
model_rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
model_rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred_rf = model_rf.predict(X_test)

# Confusion Matrix
conf_matrix_rf = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_rf)
print("Random Forest Confusion Matrix:")
print(conf_matrix_rf)

# Dier Deerlendirme Metrikleri
accuracy_rf = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_rf)
precision_rf = precision_score(y_test, y_pred_rf)
recall_rf = recall_score(y_test, y_pred_rf)
roc_auc_rf = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_rf)
class_report_rf = classification_report(y_test, y_pred_rf)
print(f'Accuracy: {accuracy_rf:.4f}')
print(f'Precision: {precision_rf:.4f}')
print(f'Recall: {recall_rf:.4f}')
print(f'ROC-AUC Score: {roc_auc_rf:.4f}')
print(f'Classification Report:\n{class_report_rf}')

Model Comparison:¶

  • Random Forest shows the highest accuracy (0.9695) and precision (0.9565), indicating it makes fewer false positive predictions compared to XGBoost, Logistic Regression, and KNN.
  • XGBoost has slightly lower accuracy and precision than Random Forest but performs well with an accuracy of 0.9576 and a precision of 0.8713.
  • K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) performs reasonably well with an accuracy of 0.9285 and a precision of 0.8193, although it has lower recall compared to Random Forest and XGBoost.
  • Logistic Regression has the lowest accuracy (0.8980) and precision (0.7419), indicating it may not be as effective in correctly predicting churn as the tree-based models.

Conclusion:¶

Based on the evaluation metrics, Random Forest emerges as the best-performing model for predicting churn in this dataset. It achieves the highest accuracy, precision, and ROC-AUC score among the evaluated models, making it the recommended choice for this prediction task.
